@node INTRO "Introduction"

This is a simple program that converts HTML documents into AmigaGuide format.

I needed a program to do this, but depite being loads of HTML to ASCII convertors, as well as plenty of AmigaGuide to HTML convertors, I found none to covert HTML to AmigaGuide. So I wrote my own ;)

Why might you need this? Well I needed for my diskmag, DoubleClick, which I produced in HTML. I wanted people who did not have the system requirements to be able to read my mag - not forgetting the fact that some may prefer to read in AmigaGuide, due to it being faster, hogging less memory, etc. I didn't want to go through the hassle of converting it myself longhand - that would take ages! With this program, it's easy!

You might think that such a progam as this is past it's time, now that most people will be able to read HTML documents reasonably well. But consider this: as far as program documentation goes (including the one you're reading now), it is almost always in AmigaGuide - not HTML. The only exceptions are, predictably, Web Browsers. This is presumeably because people find Guides easier and quicker to create, and not to mention you need a lot more system resources to run a Web Browser @{"i"}and@{"ui"} the program it documents, which is what you want to do.

But in time, as Amigas become more Powerful, I would guess that HTML would slowly replace Guides as the standard form of online documentation, and this program will be invaluable!

So there are progams that will convert from Guides to HTML? True, but if you do this, the HTML will be a mere copy almost of the Guide; to take advantage of HTML's better features, you'd need to alter it after the conversion. And then if you wanted to update the documents afterwards, you'd either have to update @{"i"}both@{"ui"} Guide and HTML (defeating the purpose of such convertors), or have to redo all your special HTML additions.

A far better way is to do your document in HTML, and then convert to AmigaGuide with this program. All the HTML bits that AmigaGuide can't do are stripped out, or done as best as possible. Then, when you update the document, only the HTML version needs to be updated, and this program re-running.

I hope you're convinced... please get in @{"touch" link ME} if you find this program useful; if I don't know anyone who's using it, I won't bother updating it!

@endnode

@node REQ "Requirements"

HTML2Guide now requires:
	- MUI Installed
	- 68020 or better
	- The 'List' command in your C: directory (which it should be)

HTML2Guide also needs a large stack to run. 32768 bytes are allocated by default, but should this not be enough (ie, it crashes when you try to convert a large directory of files or something) then try increasing the stack first (edit the script 'HTML2Guide' - 'HTML2Guide.exe' is the actual program).

@endnode

@node USAGE "How to Use This Program"

@{"b"}Explanation of Interface@{"ub"}

Include Links - You can either leave out links, or instead, include the links into the Guide. Links to HTML documents are automatically renamed with '.guide' (see batch converting, below). You can choose to only include local files (the idea being you cannot go online from an Amigaguide of course).

Include Pics - Pictures can't be placed directly into Guides, but a link to the file will be created if you wish. Again, you can choose to link only to local pictures.

Put As Pic Link - When linking to pictures, you can either display the filename, the 'ALT' text, or both in the link (if there is not ALT text, then the filename is always used instead).

Text if no Pic Link? - If there is a picture which you choose not to link to, then this option means text will be inserted saying there was a picture here.

There are two modes of operation, Single File and Entire Folder.

@{"b"}Single Folder@{"ub"}

Just select the input and output files in the gadgets below, and then click 'Go!' to convert the file.

@{"b"}Entire Folder@{"ub"}

This is the more useful way of working. When you click 'Go!', you will be asked to select a Source and Destination directory. Each file in the source directory is then scanned, and treated accordingly:

   Any ending in '.html', '.htm' or '.shtml' will be converted from HTML to AmigaGuide. The file is renamed to ending in '.guide', and placed into the destination directory.
   Any other files, be they text, gfx, programs - whatever, are copied without alteration.
   Sub-directories are just copied completely, without their contents being converted.

You will be notified if a file already exists with the same name, and asked if you wish to overwrite it.

Details of the process appear in a standard console output window - just close this when you are finished. Note that large HTML files may take time to convert, so please be patient.

@endnode

@node TODO "History and To Do"

Version 1 was released in 1997, and was a very basic version without options, and written in AMOSPRo. It couldn't handle files larger than 65k.

Version 2 - 5.4.1999

New features are:
	- Lots of options to control the output
	- Option to batch convert, or do a single file
	- Can convert files larger than 65k
	- Better handling of HTML code

Version 2 has been completely rewritten from scratch in C++ using MUI.

Future:
	- Give the option to go into and convert subdirectories, rather than blindly copying them
	- Option to halt conversion
	- Better display when converting files (rather than just text output)
	- Better handling of Tables, so that they come out reasonably in AmigaGuide!
	- Handle more of the &; tags (actually, I don't yet have a full list of all the wierd characters, so please email me if you know some that you want implemented).

Any ideas you have? Just write to @{"me" link ME}!

@endnode

